<em>Consciousness and Self-Knowledge in Medieval Philosophy</em>:
<em>Proceedings of the Society for Medieval Logic and Metaphysics</em>
(Volume 14), G. Klima and A. Hall (eds.), Newcastle: Cambridge
Scholars Publishing, 89&ndash;106.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2023, <em>A Hidden Wisdom: Medieval
Contemplatives on Self-Knowledge, Reason, Love, Persons, and
Immortality</em>, Oxford: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>Waithe, Mary Ellen (ed.), 1987&ndash;1991, <em>A History of Women
Philosophers</em>, first three volumes, Boston/Dordrecht: Kluwer
Academic Publishing.

<ul class="hanging">

<li>1987, <em>Volume 1: Ancient Women Philosophers, 600 B.C.&ndash;500
A.D</em></li>

<li>1989, <em>Volume 2: Medieval, Renaissance, and Enlightenment Women
Philosophers, A.D. 500&ndash;1600</em></li>

<li>1991, <em>Volume 3: Modern Women Philosophers,
1600&ndash;1900</em></li>
</ul></li>

<li>Waithe, Mary Ellen and Therese Boos Dykeman (eds), 2023, <em>Women
Philosophers from Non-Western Traditions: The First Four Thousand
Years</em> (Women in the History of Philosophy and Sciences), Cham:
Springer International Publishing. doi:10.1007/978-3-031-28563-9</li>

<li>Wang, Robin R., 2010, &ldquo;Ideal Womanhood in Chinese Thought
and Culture&rdquo;, <em>Philosophy Compass</em>, 5(8): 635&ndash;644.
doi:10.1111/j.1747-9991.2010.00312.x</li>

<li>Ward, Julie K., 1998, &ldquo;&lsquo;The Master&rsquo;s
Tools&rsquo;: Abolitionist Arguments of Equiano and Cugoano&rdquo;, in
 <a href="#Lott98">Lott 1998</a>:
 79&ndash;98.</li>

<li>Warnock, Mary, 1996, &ldquo;Introduction&rdquo;, to <em>Women
Philosophers</em>, Mary Warnock (ed.), London: J.M. Dent,
xxix&ndash;.xlvii.</li>

<li>Witt, Charlotte, 1993, &ldquo;Feminist Metaphysics&rdquo;, in
 <a href="#AW93">Antony and Witt 1993</a>:
 273&ndash;288 (ch. 13).</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1998, &ldquo;Form, Normativity, and Gender
in Aristotle: A Feminist Perspective&rdquo;, in
 <a href="#Freeland98">Freeland 1998</a>:
 118&ndash;137.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2006, &ldquo;Feminist Interpretations of
the Philosophical Canon&rdquo;, <em>Signs: Journal of Women in Culture
and Society</em>, 31(2): 537&ndash;552. doi:10.1086/491677</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2020, &ldquo;The Recognition Project:
Feminist History of Philosophy&rdquo;, in <em>Methodological
Reflections on Women&rsquo;s Contribution and Influence in the History
of Philosophy</em>, Sigridur Thorgeirsdottir and Ruth Edith
Hagengruber (eds), Cham: Springer International Publishing,
19&ndash;28. doi:10.1007/978-3-030-44421-1_2</li>

<li>Wollstonecraft, Mary, 1792, <em>A Vindication of the Rights of
Woman</em>, London: J. Johnson.</li>

<li>Woolhouse, Roger S., 2007, <em>Locke: A Biography</em>,
Cambridge/New York: Cambridge University Press.</li>

<li>Wootton, David, 1993, &ldquo;Introduction&rdquo;, to
 <a href="#Locke1993">Wootton 1993 [2003]</a>:
 5&ndash;122.</li>
</ul>
</div> 

